## Before You Start — Glossary

You'll see these words a lot. Here's what they actually mean, in plain English:

| Term | What it means |
|---|---|
| **Terminal / Command line** | A text-based window where you type commands instead of clicking buttons. On Linux, this is your regular terminal app. |
| **Next.js** | The framework that builds your website/app's pages, buttons, and logic. |
| **Supabase** | A hosted database + login system, so you don't have to build your own from scratch. |
| **Capacitor** | The tool that takes your finished website and wraps it inside a real Android (or iOS) app you can install on a phone. |
| **npm / npx** | Tools that come with Node.js for installing and running JavaScript packages. `npm install` downloads something; `npx` runs a tool without permanently installing it. |
| **Package / Dependency** | A piece of pre-written code someone else made that your project uses, so you don't have to write everything yourself. |
| **Repository (repo)** | A project folder that's tracked by Git, usually stored on GitHub. |
| **Build** | The process of turning your project's source code into the finished files a browser or phone can actually run. |
| **Environment variable** | A secret setting (like a password or API key) stored outside your code, so it's not accidentally shared publicly. |
| **Emulator** | A virtual Android phone that runs on your computer, so you can test your app without owning a physical phone. |
| **AGP (Android Gradle Plugin)** | The tool Android Studio uses to build Android apps. It occasionally needs updating, similar to how apps on your phone update. |

