## Part 1: Install the Tools You Need

You only need to do this section once per computer.

### Step 1.1 — Install Node.js

Node.js lets your computer run JavaScript outside a web browser — it's the engine this whole project runs on.

1. Go to [nodejs.org](https://nodejs.org) and download the **LTS** version (LTS = "Long Term Support," the stable, recommended version).
2. Install it like any other program.
3. Open your terminal and check it worked:

```bash
node -v
npm -v
```

You should see version numbers print out (not an error). **You need Node.js version 20.9 or higher.** If your version is lower, download the newer LTS release and reinstall.

### Step 1.2 — Install Git

Git tracks changes to your project and lets you save/back up your work on GitHub.

```bash
git --version
```

If this doesn't print a version number, install Git from [git-scm.com](https://git-scm.com).

### Step 1.3 — Install a Code Editor

Download and install [Visual Studio Code](https://code.visualstudio.com) — this is where you'll view and edit your project's files.

### Step 1.4 — Install Android Studio

This is the program that lets you build and test the actual Android app.

1. Download it from [developer.android.com/studio](https://developer.android.com/studio).
2. Install it and let it download the Android SDK when it first opens (this can take a while — that's normal).
3. **Find where it installed** — on Linux this varies (it might be in `/opt`, a `snap` folder, or your home directory). Find yours with:

```bash
find / -iname "studio.sh" 2>/dev/null
```

4. **Write down the full path it gives you.** You'll need it in Part 9. Example of what it looks like:

```
/opt/android-studio-2025.1.1/android-studio/bin/studio.sh
```

> 💡 Newer Android Studio versions ("Otter" 2025.2.1+) work more smoothly with this setup. Slightly older versions (like "Meerkat" 2025.1.1) also work fine — you'll just be asked to run a quick automatic upgrade the first time you open your project, covered in Part 9.

