## Part 2: Create Your Project

### Step 2.1 — Create a Home for Your Project on GitHub

1. Go to [github.com](https://github.com) and create a new, empty repository.
2. When creating it, tick the box to add a LICENSE file (recommended, but optional).
3. Copy the repository's clone link (green **Code** button → copy the HTTPS link).
4. In your terminal, download it to your computer:

```bash
git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repository>.git
cd <your-repository>
```

*(Replace `<your-username>` and `<your-repository>` with your actual GitHub details. The `cd` command just means "move into this folder.")*

### Step 2.2 — Create the Next.js Project

This single command sets up your entire website project structure automatically:

```bash
npx create-next-app@latest .
```

*(The `.` at the end means "set it up right here in this folder.")*

You'll be asked several yes/no questions. Answer like this:

```text
✔ TypeScript                  → Yes
✔ ESLint                      → Yes
✔ Tailwind CSS                → Yes
✔ App Router                  → Yes
✔ Turbopack                   → Yes
✔ Import alias (@/*)          → Yes
```

### Step 2.3 — Confirm It Works

Start a temporary local preview of your site:

```bash
npm run dev
```

Open your web browser and go to:

```
http://localhost:3000
```

You should see the default Next.js welcome page. If you do — it worked! Stop the preview by pressing `CTRL + C` in the terminal before continuing.

