## Part 6: Turn It Into an Android App

### Step 6.1 — Install Capacitor

```bash
npm install @capacitor/core
npm install -D @capacitor/cli
npm install @capacitor/android
```

Confirm it installed correctly:

```bash
npx cap --version
```

### Step 6.2 — Initialize Capacitor

```bash
npx cap init
```

You'll be asked two questions:

```text
App Name    → (a friendly name, e.g. "My App")
Package ID  → (a unique ID in reverse-domain style, e.g. com.example.myapp)
```

This creates a new file called `capacitor.config.ts`.

### Step 6.3 — Fix the Config File

The file Capacitor just created points to the wrong folder by default. Open `capacitor.config.ts` and replace its contents with this exact version:

```typescript
import type { CapacitorConfig } from '@capacitor/cli';

const config: CapacitorConfig = {
  appId: 'com.example.app',
  appName: 'myapp',
  webDir: 'out'
};

export default config;
```

Change `appId` and `appName` to match what you chose in Step 6.2. **The important part is `webDir: 'out'`** — this must say `out`, not `public` (which is what Capacitor puts there by default, and it's wrong).

### Step 6.4 — Add the Android Platform

```bash
npx cap add android
```

This creates a new `android/` folder containing a full native Android project.

> If this step fails with an error mentioning `index.html` or `capacitor.plugins.json`, it means Step 5.2 (the build) or Step 6.3 (fixing `webDir`) wasn't completed first. Fix those, then run:
> ```bash
> rm -rf android
> npx cap add android
> ```

