## Part 7: Connect Your Database (Supabase)

### Step 7.1 — Create a Supabase Project

1. Go to [supabase.com](https://supabase.com) and create a free account if you don't have one.
2. Click **New Project**.
3. Wait for it to finish setting up (a progress bar will show — this takes a couple of minutes).

### Step 7.2 — Get Your Project's Keys

Inside your new Supabase project, go to **Settings → API**. You'll see two values you need:

- **Project URL**
- **Anon (public) key**

### Step 7.3 — Add Them to Your Project

In your project folder, create a new file called `.env.local` and paste in:

```env
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_URL=YOUR_PROJECT_URL
NEXT_PUBLIC_SUPABASE_ANON_KEY=YOUR_ANON_KEY
```

Replace the placeholder text with your real values from Step 7.2.

> 🔒 **Never share this file or upload it to GitHub.** It's already excluded automatically by the `.gitignore` file that Next.js created for you.

### Step 7.4 — Set Up the Supabase Connection Files

Create a new folder: `lib/supabase/`

Inside it, create three files: `client.ts`, `server.ts`, and `middleware.ts`. *(A developer will fill in the actual code for these — this guide covers the setup scaffolding, not the code itself.)*

> ⚠️ **Important naming rule:** the file that runs automatically on every page request must be named `proxy.ts` and placed at the very root of your project (not inside `lib/supabase/`). This is a naming requirement specific to the version of Next.js used in this guide — older tutorials call this file `middleware.ts`, but that name no longer works at the project root.

