## Part 9: Run the App on a Phone or Emulator

### Step 9.1 — Sync Your Latest Changes

Every time you change your app's code, run these two commands before testing on Android:

```bash
npm run build
npx cap sync
```

### Step 9.2 — Open Android Studio

Use the path you wrote down in Step 1.4, typed directly into this command:

```bash
CAPACITOR_ANDROID_STUDIO_PATH=/path/to/your/studio.sh npx cap open android
```

Real example:

```bash
CAPACITOR_ANDROID_STUDIO_PATH=/opt/android-studio-2025.1.1/android-studio/bin/studio.sh npx cap open android
```

> 💡 We tried saving this as a permanent setting so you wouldn't have to type it every time, but it didn't reliably work. Typing the full command above each time is the version that actually works — consider saving it as a text note or a shell shortcut (called an "alias") for convenience.

### Step 9.3 — Handle the First-Time Update Prompt

The first time Android Studio opens your project, you may see a small banner near the top saying something like:

> **"Project update recommended — Android Gradle plugin version X has an upgrade available."**

This is completely normal and expected. Click **Start AGP Upgrade Assistant**, accept the suggested version, and click **Run selected steps**.

If instead you see a message saying **"This step is blocked — Cannot find AGP version in build files,"** the automatic assistant can't read the file format. Fix it manually:

1. Open `android/build.gradle`. Find a line like:
   ```gradle
   classpath 'com.android.tools.build:gradle:8.7.2'
   ```
   Change the version number to a newer one, e.g. `8.11.2` or `8.13.0`.
2. Open `android/gradle/wrapper/gradle-wrapper.properties`. Find the `distributionUrl` line and update the version number in it similarly, e.g. `gradle-8.14.3-all.zip`.
3. In Android Studio, click **File → Sync Project with Gradle Files**.

Wait for the bottom status bar to say **"Sync succeeded."** That means it's ready.

### Step 9.4 — Set Up a Virtual Phone (Emulator)

1. In Android Studio, click the **Device Manager** icon on the right sidebar (looks like a phone).
2. Click **Create Device**, pick a phone model (e.g. Pixel 8), and pick a system image (Android version) to download if you don't have one yet.
3. Click **Finish**.

*(Alternatively, you can plug in a real Android phone via USB with "Developer Options" and "USB Debugging" turned on.)*

### Step 9.5 — Run the App

1. At the top of Android Studio, pick your emulator or device from the dropdown menu.
2. Click the green **▶ Run** button (or press `Shift + F10`).
3. Wait — the first run can take a few minutes while it builds and installs.

Your app should now open on the emulator or phone. 🎉

